  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Accepting Below-Threshold Salary</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The S$5,000 minimum is just the start. Older candidates need higher salaries. Use MOM's Self-Assessment Tool before accepting any offer. An EP rejection wastes everyone's time and may affect future applications.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Understanding COMPASS Impact</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Your personal qualifications matter, but so does your employer's profile. A startup with few local employees may struggle to pass COMPASS even for qualified candidates. Research potential employers.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Employer Insurance is Comprehensive</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The mandatory minimum (S$15,000 inpatient) is quite basic. A serious hospital stay in Singapore can cost S$50,000+. Review your employer's actual policy and consider supplementary coverage.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing Dependant Pass Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Spouse and children can only join if you earn S$6,000+ monthly. For Long-Term Visit Pass (parents), you need S$12,000+. Plan family moves carefully based on your salary level.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Letting IPA Expire</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The In-Principle Approval is valid for 6 months. You must enter Singapore and complete EP formalities within this window. If it expires, your employer must reapply.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Singapore -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Singapore</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Singapore has world-class healthcare with excellent hospitals and specialists. The system is primarily private for foreigners—there's no public healthcare access for EP holders. Your employer's insurance and any supplementary coverage fund your care.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Singapore's Healthcare System</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Private Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Mount Elizabeth, Raffles Hospital, Gleneagles—these are world-class facilities with short waits and excellent care. Most expat insurance covers private hospitals. Costs are high but so is quality.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Restructured (Public) Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Singapore General Hospital, NUH, Tan Tock Seng—these are government-run but operate as private for foreigners. You pay unsubsidized rates. Quality is excellent; costs are lower than private but still significant.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">GP Clinics</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Private GP clinics are everywhere. Walk-in consultations cost S$50-100. Many accept insurance direct billing. For minor issues, GPs are convenient and affordable.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Costs Without Insurance</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Singapore healthcare is expensive without coverage:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> S$50-100</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist consultation:</strong> S$150-400</li>
      <li><strong>ER visit:</strong> S$500-2,000</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital day (private):</strong> S$1,000-3,000</li>
      <li><strong>Surgery:</strong> S$5,000-50,000+</li>
      <li><strong>Childbirth:</strong> S$10,000-25,000</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>High quality worth the cost:</strong> Singapore ranks among the world's best healthcare systems. Doctor training is rigorous, facilities are modern, and wait times are minimal. Many expats find the quality exceeds their home countries.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to arrange my own health insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Since January 2023, employers are legally required to provide medical insurance for EP holders (minimum S$15,000/year inpatient coverage). You may want to supplement this with additional coverage, but the basics are handled by your employer.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is COMPASS and why does it matter?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          COMPASS is a points-based framework for EP applications since September 2023. You must score 40+ points across criteria including salary, qualifications, and employer factors. Even qualified candidates can be rejected if their employer's profile doesn't contribute enough points.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my spouse work in Singapore?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If your salary is S$6,000+, your spouse can get a Dependant Pass (DP). DP holders can work with a Letter of Consent (LOC) from MOM—this is relatively easy to obtain if an employer wants to hire them.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How hard is it to get permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Permanent Residence (PR) in Singapore is discretionary and competitive. EP holders can apply after 6 months but approval rates are low. Factors include salary, sector, community involvement, and Singapore's economic needs. Most applicants apply multiple times before success.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on an EP?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your new employer must apply for a new EP for you. You can remain in Singapore during the transition. The new EP must meet current requirements and pass COMPASS. There's no need to leave the country.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if I lose my job?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Your EP is tied to your employer—if you lose your job, you have a short grace period to find a new employer willing to apply for your EP, or you must leave Singapore. There's no specific timeframe stated by MOM, but realistically you have weeks, not months.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Singapore's Employment Pass offers access to one of Asia's most dynamic economies with world-class healthcare, low taxes, and excellent quality of life. The COMPASS framework has made requirements more transparent but also more demanding—your employer's profile matters as much as your own qualifications.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare is handled well: employers must provide insurance, and Singapore's medical facilities are excellent. The main consideration is whether employer-provided coverage is comprehensive enough, especially for maternity, mental health, or pre-existing conditions. Many expats supplement with international plans.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For professionals in finance, tech, and regional business roles, Singapore offers compelling opportunities. The lack of a clear PR pathway is a consideration for long-term planning, but the immediate benefits—low taxes, safety, efficiency—make it attractive for many skilled workers.
    </p>

